John Edwards: Language Skills Essential for World Citizens
Independent schools in Scotland maintain a track record of academic excellence, and this continues in 2018 with another set of outstanding test results, reinforced by personal and team success in sports, arts, music and other areas of community practice.
With over 30,000 students across Scotland, these schools, represented by the Scottish Council of Independent Schools (SCIS), strive to provide the best level of service to students and parents.
Independent schools strive to prepare their students for further and higher education, for the careers they choose and for their place as citizens of the world.
As an education sector that is able to design and implement a customized curriculum, we find that modern languages continue to gain popularity as a desired field of study at school.
Nelson Mandela once said, “If you talk to a man in a language he understands, it goes into his head.
If you talk to a man in his own language, it goes into his heart.”
This is an important reminder that we cannot rely solely on English when we want to build relationships and trust with people from other countries.
From the results of last year’s tests, you can see that languages are at the top of the tables with the highest success rates in independent schools.
A total of 68% of students who studied foreign languages scored a high A.
Data collected from the 74 schools members of SCIS showed that 72 percent of students achieved a high A in Mandarin, as did 72 percent of those who studied German, 69 percent of those who studied French and 63 percent of those who studied Spanish.
These data show that independent schools in Scotland support foreign languages as essential skills that children and young people will undoubtedly need in the future.
Today the field of languages as an elective subject is considered at the same level as STEM subjects (Science, Technology, Engineering and Mathematics) in the curricula of independent schools and elsewhere.
A 2014 survey by the British Council on Employment and Skills found that of the reasons employers cited Kodi for filling vacancies, 17 percent were attributed to a lack of language skills.
Thus, increasingly, language skills become an essential requirement to prepare students for future careers.
Given the rising demands for languages for future job opportunities, these skills are essential in a world of globalization.
No matter what career a person chooses, if he or she has learned a second language, he or she will have a significant advantage in the future thanks to this lifelong ability.
The ability to communicate directly with people from foreign countries automatically stabilizes a person in an advantageous position over competitors.
According to a YouGov survey of more than 4,000 adults in the UK in 2013, 75 percent could not speak a foreign language enough to have a conversation, and French was the only language with a two-digit number of speakers, 15 percent.
That’s why it’s important to invest in teaching children languages today.
Knowledge of many languages, especially those of developing countries, will give children a better chance of finding meaningful employment.
Within Scotland, each school will be different as to the languages taught in it.
Some schools will focus on the more classical modern languages, while others will learn languages that are considered most important for the UK in looking forward to the 20th century, such as Mandarin and Japanese.
Whatever the child’s field of interest, there will always be a variety of languages to choose from in independent schools, with a team of teachers specializing in the field.
Independent schools in Scotland are committed to providing a learning environment that prepares children and equips them with the skills needed to succeed, in any foreseeable future.
It cannot be denied today, in a global business environment, that languages continue to be of vital importance for the future of the country, and therefore this fact should be reflected in education.
Indeed, modern languages should be viewed as “international communication skills.”
Independent schools will continue to offer these levels of choice, diversity and excellence to Scotland’s children.
It's the order of the hour.
John Edward is head of the Scottish Council of Independent Schools.
