North Korea says 'under no circumstances' it will not disarm unilaterally without trust
North Korea’s foreign minister said on Saturday at the United Nations that continued sanctions were deepening its mistrust of the United States and that there was no way the country would give up its nuclear weapons unilaterally under the circumstances.
At the annual United Nations General Assembly, Ri Yong Ho announced that North Korea had taken “significant goodwill measures” in the past year, such as halting nuclear missile tests, dismantling the nuclear test site and committing to no longer developing nuclear weapons and nuclear technology.
“But we don’t see any consistent response from the United States,” he said.
“Without trust in the United States, we cannot be sure about our national defense and under such conditions we will not first unilaterally disarm ourselves of nuclear weapons.”
While he repeated North Korea’s well-known complaints about the U.S.’s opposition to a “graded” approach to nuclear disarmament, whereby North Korea would be rewarded while taking gradual steps, his statement seems important in that it has not rejected nuclear disarmament on the brink, as North Korea has done in the past.
Referring to a joint declaration made by Kim Jong-un and Donald Trump at the first-ever summit between a sitting U.S. president and a North Korean leader in Singapore on June 12, in which Kim pledged to work toward “denuclearization of the Korean peninsula” while Trump promised to protect North Korea’s security.
North Korea has sought an official end to the 1950-53 Korean War, but the United States has said North Korea must first give up its nuclear weapons.
The United States has also opposed calls to reduce international sanctions on North Korea.
“The U.S. insists on ‘nuclear disarmament first’ and increases sanctions pressure to achieve its goal through coercion, and even opposes ‘declaring an end to the war,’” Ri said.
“The perception that sanctions can make us kneel is a dream in the assemblage of people who are ignorant of us.
But the problem is that the escalating sanctions deepen our mistrust.”
Ri made no mention of plans for a second summit between Kim and Trump, which the U.S. president stressed in a speech at the United Nations earlier this week.
Instead, the minister stressed three meetings between Kim and South Korean leader Moon Jae-in in the past five months, adding: “If the other side on the denuclearization issue were South Korea and not the United States, the denuclearization of the Korean peninsula would not have reached such a dead end.”
However, Ri’s speech was dramatically different from last year’s, when he told the U.N. General Assembly that a U.S. missile attack by North Korea was inevitable after Mr. Trump called Kim a “rocket man” on a suicide mission.
This year at the United Nations, Trump, who last year threatened "total destruction" of North Korea, praised Kim for his courage in taking steps to denuclearize, but said there was still a lot of work to be done and that sanctions must remain in place until North Korea's nuclear disarmament.
On Wednesday, Trump said he did not have a specific timeframe for that, adding: “If it takes two years, three years, or five months, it doesn’t matter.”
China and Russia have said the U.N. Security Council should reward North Korea for its actions.
U.S. Secretary of State Mike Pompeo told the U.N. Security Council on Thursday that “enforcement of Security Council sanctions must continue with determination and unimpeded until we achieve complete and verified nuclear disarmament.”
The Security Council has unanimously supported the imposition of sanctions on North Korea since 2006 in an attempt to block funding for its ballistic and nuclear missile programs.
