The National Foundation of Scotland Listens to The Secret Life of Bats
A new study at a mansion in the mountains of Scotland aims to reveal how bats use the landscape to hunt for their food.
It is hoped that the findings will shed new light on the behavior of the unique flying mammals and help guide future conservation activities.
The study, conducted by scientists at the National Foundation of Scotland, will track common bats and European phones, as well as brown, long-eared Dubenton bats in Invero Gardens in Worcester Ross.
Special recording devices will be placed at key locations around the property to track bat activities throughout the season.
The National Health Service (NHS) team and volunteers will also conduct mobile surveys using manual detectors.
A specialized sound analysis of all recordings will determine the frequencies of bat calls and which of the species is responsible for them.
Next, a map of the habitats will be drawn to create a detailed picture on the scale of the landscape, of their behavior patterns.
Rob Dewar, a conservation consultant for the National Foundation of Scotland (NTS), hopes the results will reveal which areas of life are most important to bats and how each species uses them.
This information will help determine the benefits of the livelihood management work, such as the creation of meadows and how best to preserve forest areas for bats and other related species.
Bat populations in Scotland and across the UK have declined considerably over the last century.
They are under threat from development and construction works, which affect nesting and the loss of living areas.
Wind turbines and lighting can also pose a risk, and the same is true for fly traps and certain chemical treatments of building materials, as well as attacks by domestic cats.
In fact, bats are not blind.
However, due to their nocturnal hunting habits, bat ears are more useful when it comes to catching prey.
They use a sophisticated echo detection technique to locate insects and identify obstacles to their flight path.
The NTS Foundation, which is responsible for the care of over 270 historic buildings, 38 important gardens and 760,000 acres of land across the country, takes bats very seriously.
