Syria ‘ready’ to return refugees, says foreign minister
Syria says it is ready for the voluntary return of refugees and calls for aid to rebuild the country devastated by more than seven years of war.
In a speech to the United Nations, Foreign Minister Walid al-Muallem said conditions in the country were improving.
“Today, the situation on the ground is stable and safer thanks to the progress achieved in the war on terror,” he said.
The government continues to rebuild the areas destroyed by the terrorists in order to restore the situation to normal.
All conditions now exist for refugees to return voluntarily to the country they left because of terrorism and unilateral economic measures aimed at harming their daily lives and livelihoods.
According to the United Nations, more than 5.5 million Syrians have fled the country since the start of the war in 2011.
An additional six million people still living in the country are in need of humanitarian assistance.
Al-Muallem said the Syrian regime would welcome assistance to rebuild the destroyed country.
But he stressed that the regime would not receive conditional aid or assistance from countries that funded the rebels.
Europe won the Ryder Cup in Paris.
The European team won the 2018 Ryder Cup and defeated the U.S. team with a final score of 16.5–10.5 at the National Golf Course outside Paris, France.
The U.S. has so far lost six times in a row on European soil and has not won the Ryder Cup in Europe since 1993.
Europe again won the crown when the team of Danish captain Thomas Bjorn reached the 14.5 points it took to beat the United States.
American star Phil Mikaelson, who struggled for almost the entire tournament, sent his T-stake into the water in the 16th hole of the Far-3, losing the game against Francesco Molinari.
Italian golfer Molinari shined in all his rounds, becoming one of the four players to reach 5-0-0 since the start of the tournament in the current structure, in 1979.
American actor Jordan Spit was defeated 5th and 4th by the lowest-ranked player in the European team, Thorbjorn Olsen of Denmark.
Dustin Johnson, the world's No. 1 player, lost 2 and 1 to Ian Polter from England, which may be the last time he plays in the Ryder Cup.
With eight Ryder Cup seniors, Spanish Sergio García has become the European player with the highest number of wins in tournaments with 25.5 career points.
“I don’t usually cry, but today I can’t help it.
It's been a rough year.
So I'm grateful to Thomas for choosing me and believing in me.
I'm so happy, so happy to have the trophy back.
It’s a team and I’m glad I was able to help,” Garcia said emotionally after the European victory.
He passes the torch to his countryman John Ram, who defeated American legend Tiger Woods 2 and 1 in the singles game on Sunday.
“The immense pride I feel is defeating the Tiger Woods I watched growing up,” Ram, 23, said.
Woods lost all four games in France and now has a record of 13-21-3, culminating in the Ryder Cup in his career.
These are strange statistics from one of the best players of all time, who has won 14 major titles, with only Jack Niklaus in front of him.
The U.S. team struggled throughout the weekend to find their way through the lawns, except for Patrick Reid, Justin Thomas and Tony Pinaw who played high-level golf throughout the tournament.
U.S. National Team Captain Jim Furick said after his team’s disappointing performance, “I’m proud of these guys, they fought.
There was a moment this morning when we put pressure on Europe.
We failed.
Well done to Thomas.
He's a great captain.
All 12 players played well.
We'll regroup, I'll work with the American Golf Association and our Ryder Cup committee, and we'll move on.
I love these 12 guys and I'm proud to be captain.
I need to take my hat off.
We're defeated."
Red tide update: concentrations are decreasing in Pinellas, Manati and Sarasota
The latest report from the Florida Wildlife and Fisheries Commission shows a general decline in red tide concentrations in part of the Tampa Bay area.
According to the FWC, more scattered flowering conditions have been reported in Pinellas, Manati, Sarasota, Charlotte and Collier counties – indicating decreasing concentrations.
The red tide bloom extends over about 130 miles from the coastline, from North Pinellas County to South Lee County.
The plots can be found about 10 miles off the coast of Hillsboro County, but in a few smaller locations compared to last week.
The red tide was also observed in Pascoe County.
Medium concentrations on the coastline or off the coast of Pinellas County were reported last week, low to medium concentrations off the coastline of Hillsborough County, background concentrations to high concentrations in Manati County, background concentrations to high concentrations on the coastline or off the coast of Sarasota County, only concentrations from low to medium concentrations, background concentrations to medium concentrations in Sarasota County.
Reports of respiratory stimuli continue from Pinellas, Manati, Sarasota, Lee and Collier counties.
No airway stimulation has been reported in northwestern Florida over the past week.
